properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility and rapidly accumulating snow possible in snow squalls. Total snowfall: generally 2 to 4 cm, except locally 10 cm or more in snow squalls. Time span: until this evening. Remarks: Onshore flurries will continue today with occasional snow squalls and gusty northwesterly winds. Visibility may be suddenly reduced to near zero in snow and blowing snow under the squalls. Conditions will begin to improve this evening. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Snow squall watches are issued when conditions are favourable for the formation of bands of snow that could produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: More snow expected on Sunday. Locations: much of Newfoundland (excluding the Great Northern Peninsula). Total snowfall: generally 10 to 15 cm, with potentially more than 20 cm over some areas. Remarks: A fast-moving weather system will bring snow to much of the island on Sunday. While it is too soon to determine exactly where the heaviest accumulations will occur, the potential exists for significant amounts over some locations. The snow may also change to rain over southern coastal areas before ending. Gusty easterly winds accompanying the snow will result in blowing snow and reduced visibilities. Conditions are expected to improve over southern and western Newfoundland on Sunday afternoon, and elsewhere Sunday night. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Northwesterly winds up to 50 km/h are bringing blizzard conditions with near zero visibility in blowing snow to communities in southern Kivalliq. These blizzard conditions will gradually improve later this morning or early this afternoon. Overnight, temperatures dropped to minus 40 and lower over southern Kivalliq. These frigid temperatures combined with the gusty northwest winds will give extreme wind chill values of minus 60 to minus 65. These extreme cold values will last through to Sunday morning. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Weather Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Winter Weather Travel Advisory in effect for today. An intense band of snow associated with the passage of a cold front is expected to move across Far Northern Ontario today. This band of snow may extend from Winisk River to Sachigo Lake this morning and is expected to move southward throughout the day, reaching Lansdowne House to Cat Lake by this evening. A total snowfall accumulation up to 10 cm is possible. Hazardous travel conditions are expected due to near zero visibilities in bursts of heavy snow and blowing snow. Consider post-poning non essential travel until conditions improve. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

Temperatures near minus 40 combined with northwesterly winds of 15 to 20 km/h are bringing extreme wind chill values of minus 55 and colder to Sanirajak and Igloolik. Igloolik's temperature will moderate today, but Sanirajak will see extreme wind chill values into Saturday morning. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
